<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920220-0088</DOCNO><DOCID>920220-0088.</DOCID><HL>   Remaining Defendants   Settle MiniScribe Lawsuit   ----   A Wall Street Journal News Roundup</HL><DATE>02/20/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2</SO><CO>   MINQE</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)SECURITIES (SCR)</IN><NS>BANKRUPTCY DECLARATIONS AND PROCEEDINGS (BCY)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)</NS><RE>CALIFORNIA (CA)COLORADO (CO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)PACIFIC RIM (PRM)TEXAS (TX)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   The remaining defendants in a suit brought by bondholdersin the defunct MiniScribe Corp. agreed to a settlement thatvoided a jury's award of more than $330 million in damagesagainst the defendants.   The settlement was reached Tuesday with the San Franciscoinvestment banking firm of Hambrecht and Quist; the firm'spresident and co-chief executive, William R. Hambrecht; andMiniScribe's former chairman, Q.T. Wiles. A similarsettlement was reached Monday with MiniScribe's formeraccounting firm, Coopers andamp; Lybrand, which had been assessedmore than $200 million in damages.</LP><TEXT>   The defendants declined to specify the amount of thesettlement, as did the bondholders' lawyer, Joseph R. Jamailof Houston.   As part of the settlement, state district Judge RoyEngelke of Galveston set aside the verdict handed up Feb. 4,the first to be returned in the dozen or more suits filed bystockholders and bondholders against MiniScribe officers,directors and advisers. Most of those suits are pending infederal court in Denver. The disk-drive maker, which wasbased in Longmont, Colo., sought bankruptcy-court protectionin January 1990 after an internal company investigation foundthat senior management &quot;perpetrated a massive fraud&quot; on thecompany, its directors and investors.</TEXT></DOC>